The Gerund and Gerundive

The following essential points of difference between the gerund and gerundive may be of service to beginners.

1. The gerund is a verbal noun, the gerundive a verbal adjective.

2. The gerund, being a verbal noun, may stand alone or with an object.

3. The gerundivc as a verbal adjective is used only in agree- ment with a noun.

4. As a rule, only the genitive of the gerund and the ablative without a preposition admit 3 direct object. In other caseS, and often in the former, the gerundive construction is preferred.

5. To change a gerund with 3 direct object into the correspond- ing gerundive construction, put the direct object in the case of the gertrud, and use the gerundive in adjective agreement with it.
